SIMPLE: pith
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pith
<hw>Pith</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>pi<?/a</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>pit</ets> pith, kernel, LG. <ets>peddik</ets>. Cf.
<er>Pit</er> a kernel.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The
soft spongy substance in the center of the stems of many plants and
trees, especially those of the dicotyledonous or exogenous classes. It
consists of cellular tissue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The spongy interior
substance of a feather.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The
spinal cord; the marrow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence: The which contains the strength of life; the
vital or essential part; concentrated force; vigor; strength;
importance; <as>as, the speech lacked <ex>pith</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Enterprises of great <qex>pith</qex> and moment.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pith paper</b></col>. <cd>Same as <cref>Rice
paper</cref>, under <er>Rice</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pith</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pith
<hw>Pith</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>To destroy
the central nervous system of (an animal, as a frog), as by passing a
stout wire or needle up and down the vertebral canal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pithecanthropus</ent>⟦br⟧
